.TH GROOT 1 "March 2026" "groot 1.5.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
groot \- a friendly sudo wrapper for Linux

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B groot
.br
.B groot
<command> [args]
.br
.B groot
[\-\-dry\-run] [\-\-shell\-after] <command> [args]
.br
.B groot
[\-\-help] [\-\-version]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B groot
is a lightweight Bash utility that provides a clean, expressive interface for
privilege elevation. It wraps
.B sudo
with predictable behaviour, optional literal\-command execution, and a safe
dry\-run preview mode. It is designed for administrators, developers, and
power users who want a simple, memorable way to elevate privileges without
typing long commands.

When invoked with no arguments,
.B groot
opens a full root login shell. When given a command, it executes that command
as root using
.B sudo.
When used with
.BR \-\-shell\-after ,
groot executes the command literally and then opens a root login shell.
When used with
.BR \-\-dry\-run ,
groot prints what it would execute without running anything.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show help information and exit.

.TP
.B \-\-version
Show version information and exit.

.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run
Do not execute anything. Instead, print the exact
.B sudo
command that groot would run. This applies to both normal and literal modes.

.TP
.B \-\-shell\-after
Execute the provided command literally, preserving quoting, semicolons,
pipes, and other shell characters, then open a root login shell.

.TP
.B \-\-dry\-run \-\-shell\-after
Combine both behaviours: print the literal command groot would run, followed
by a note indicating that a root login shell would be opened. No commands are
executed.

.SH BEHAVIOUR
.PP
.B No arguments:
.RS
Opens a root login shell:
.br
.B sudo su \-
.RE

.PP
.B Normal command execution:
.RS
Executes the command as root:
.br
.B sudo <command> [args]
.RE

.PP
.B Literal execution with shell:
.RS
Reconstructs the command literally using
.B printf '%q'
and executes it as root, then opens a root login shell.
.RE

.PP
.B Dry\-run:
.RS
Prints the exact sudo command groot would run, without executing anything.
.RE

.PP
.B Dry\-run + shell\-after:
.RS
Prints the literal sudo command and indicates that a root shell would follow.
No commands are executed.
.RE

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Open a root login shell:
.RS
.B groot
.RE

.TP
Run a command as root:
.RS
.B groot dnf update
.RE

.TP
Run a command literally, then enter a root shell:
.RS
.B groot \-\-shell\-after 'echo "hello; id"'
.RE

.TP
Preview what groot would run:
.RS
.B groot \-\-dry\-run dnf install nginx
.RE

.TP
Preview literal execution and shell\-after:
.RS
.B groot \-\-dry\-run \-\-shell\-after 'echo "hello; id"'
.RE

.SH SECURITY
.B groot
does not bypass authentication. It relies entirely on the system's existing
.B sudo
configuration. No passwords are stored, and no security mechanisms are
modified. Literal commands are reconstructed safely using
.B printf '%q'.
Unquoted semicolons are interpreted by the user's shell before groot runs.

